1. What is DNS?
DNS (Domain Name System) converts domain names into IP addresses.
-> Humans remember names: api.myapp.com
 -> Machines understand IPs: 203.0.113.10
DNS is the translator between humans and machines.

2. DNS Resolution Flow (Step by Step)
What happens when user hits api.myapp.com?
	1. Browser / App asks a DNS Resolver
	2. Resolver checks local cache
	3. If not found → goes to:
		○ Root DNS Server → “Who manages .com?”
		○ TLD Server (.com) → “Who manages myapp.com?”
		○ Authoritative DNS → “Here is the IP”
	4. IP returned → browser connects to server
 System design point:
	DNS resolution usually happens in milliseconds due to caching.

 3. Important DNS Records (Interview MUST-KNOW)
A Record
Domain → IPv4
api.myapp.com → 203.0.113.10

AAAA Record
Domain → IPv6

CNAME
Alias to another domain
api.myapp.com → myapp-lb.aws.com
Used heavily with Load Balancers & CDNs

NS
Which DNS servers control the domain

TXT
Verification, security (SPF, DKIM)

4. TTL – The Most Important DNS Setting
TTL = Time To Live (cache duration)
TTL	Pros	Cons
Low (30–60s)	Fast failover	More DNS traffic
High (1h–24h)	Stable, cheap	Slow changes

System design rule:
	Lower TTL during migration, higher TTL during normal operations.

 5. DNS as Load Balancer (Global Traffic Routing)
a) Round Robin DNS
Returns multiple IPs
❌ No real-time load awareness
❌ Caching causes uneven traffic

b) Geo / Latency-Based DNS
User routed to nearest region
✔️ Lower latency
❌ Geo detection not 100% accurate

c) Weighted DNS
90% → old system
10% → new system (canary release)
Weights are approximate, not exact.

6. DNS + CDN (Very Important in Real Systems)
Typical flow:
www.myapp.com → CDN → Edge Server → Origin Server

DNS routes user to nearest CDN edge.
:- Benefits:
	• Faster response
	• Less load on backend
	• Global scalability

7. DNS in Microservices & Kubernetes
Example: payment-service.default.svc.cluster.local

Why DNS matters here:
	• Pods change IPs frequently
	• DNS gives stable service names
	• Enables service discovery
Java corner case:
JVM caches DNS → may delay failover if TTL is ignored.

8. DNS Security & Failure Scenarios
What can go wrong?
	• DNS outage → entire site unreachable
	• Wrong TTL → traffic stuck on old servers
	• DNS cache poisoning
Protection:
	• Multiple name servers
	• Strong registrar security
	• DDoS-protected DNS providers

Real-World System Design Example
Global E-commerce App
www.shop.com  → CDN
api.shop.com  → Global Load Balancer
DNS routing:
- Canada → us-east
- India → ap-south
Failover:
- ap-south down → us-east
TTL:
